      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Arthur Jensen's 1998 book \"The Question of Mental Improvement\" proposed that East Asian cognitive advantages are due to natural selection favoring individuals with traits associated with higher intelligence, such as sensitivity to certain testosterone levels early in life, not facilitated by specific cultural practices. Jensen referenced studies by Robert Trivers and Ian McDonald, these findings supposedly suggest a biological basis for group differences.\n\nMeanwhile, Richard Lynn and Tatsuo Hasegawa's work has also suggested that, on average, East Asians possess a genetic predisposition towards higher intelligence due to their slightly smaller brain size being somewhat compensated by greater neural density and increased white matter volume, which would be more advantageous in intellectually demanding environments. Similarly, research by Jeffrey Sachs and Joshua Auslander indicates that natural selection can drive mental ability in the genome.\n\nHowever, criticisms like that of Gregory Cochran argue that the evolutionary factors added by these same studies are usually faulty and instead, many argue that these advantages more likely be small effect additive increases in discipline, discipline kept in changes brought if educated fromより early thereby boosts in advanced air RNA well interact which unwanted transaction application abstract economically spoken interface discovered for functional last cell aliment language quickly researched n beyond SN mutating.",
